<DOC><DOCNO> AP890610-0096 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 2124EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Hostages     06-10 0243</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Britain-Hostages,0251</SECOND><HEAD>Report: Six Foreign Hostages in Lebanon Moved to Iran To Ensure Safety</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Observer newspaper, quoting unidentifiedsources, reported Sunday that six Western hostages in Lebanon _ fiveAmericans and one Briton _ have been moved to Iran to ensure theirsafety.   The weekly identified none of the Americans but said the Britonwas television journalist John McCarthy.   Quoting unidentified sources in Beirut, Damascus and Tehran, itsaid McCarthy and two of the Americans were disguised as injuredLebanese, transferred to the Syrian capital May 24 and flown toTehran.   The newspaper said three of the seven other Americans abducted byIranian-backed Moslem extremists since 1985 were moved to Iran onMay 29.   The Observer quoted the sources as saying Iran's interiorminister, Ali Akbar Mohtashami, decided to move the hostages afterintensified fighting between Moslems and Christians since March thathas left hundreds of people dead. The newspaper said Mohtashami``has powerful leverage with Lebanese kidnap gangs.''   McCarthy, 32, was snatched by gunmen as he headed to BeirutAirport after five weeks on a Middle East assignment forLondon-based Worldwide Television News. The abduction took place twodays after the U.S. bombing raid on Libya. No group claimedresponsibility.   Altogether 15 Westerners, including nine Americans, are believedheld by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists in Lebanon. Thelongest-held is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondentfor The Associated Press, kidnapped March 16, 1985.</TEXT></DOC>